                        "content": "The nurse is caring for a client with esophageal varices. Knowing the pathophysiology of this disorder, which other associated condition would the nurse suspect in the client?",
                        "subjectId": "ad5ab04c79144c0ea9b83385308c3b1d",
                        "difficultyIds": "11797937e327eb6d913faa80427c566b",
                        "difficulty": "考试范围-Analyzing 分析",
                        "textAnalysis": "Rationale:\nEsophageal varices occur when esophageal veins become distended and tortuous from increased portal pressure. Cirrhosis is a common cause of portal hypertension and subsequent esophageal varices. Bleeding from esophageal varices is considered a medical emergency, and the nurse needs to monitor the client closely for signs and symptoms of bleeding. Eliminate options 2, 3, and 4 because these conditions are not associated with esophageal varices. Therefore, since cirrhosis results in portal hypertension and the distention of esophageal veins, option 1 is the correct answer.",
                        "id": "86a09f2bc7054b10b6a5e373fe1b2ca6",
                        "mark": "0",
                        "collectionState": "0"
                    }
